    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-07-24T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-07-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1426"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1426">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 817.00/1784.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Attorney General</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-07-24">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 24, 1912</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: The American Legation at Managua has been
                    informed that General Luis Mena, Secretary of War in the Cabinet of President
                    Díaz of Nicaragua, has recently, without the knowledge of the President of that
                    country, placed an order for the account of the Government of Nicaragua with
                    Park Benzinger and Company of New York for two gasoline launches, each armed
                    with six Colt machine guns and equipped with a large amount of provisions. It is
                    reported that this order refers to the launches <hi rend="italic">Zorayda</hi>
                    and <hi rend="italic">Kasagi</hi>, to be purchased from the Jennings Yacht
                    Brokerage Company, and amounts in all to $30,000.</p>
                <p>As this may be preparatory to a revolutionary movement against the present
                    Government of Nicaragua, and in order that the Legation may be advised as to the
                    truth of this report, I have the honor to request that the result of such
                    investigation as you may deem expedient to conduct in this connection be
                    communicated to this Department at your early convenience.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">P. C. Knox.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
